\chapter{Discourse Around F\&C and Creoles and Cajuns}
  \label{chap:discourse}
  % Justify this chapter

  \section{Racialized discourse}
    %% What themes would we expect to observe

    % Racialized people being able to describe hardships that only they faced
      % Living in neglected, crime-ridden neighborhoods
        % Becker (2014) quoted a 29 year old participant who spoke about playing a game as a kid where they would choose colors and count up crack vials of that color on their way to some destination (46).
        % Foxy Brown spoke about how her friend had been killed in a gang-related shooting (Rickford & McNair-Knox 1994:243).
      % False accusations
        % One of Labov & Harris's (1986) participants, a Black man from a middle-class family, recalled an incident where he was accused of stealing instruments (3).

    % Characterizing racialized people negatively without using racist terms
      % Due to her appearance and speech, Rachel Jeantel was characterized by some of the public as looking "irritated", having "absolutely no respect", being "dumber than a box of rocks," and even as "playing right into stereotypes about Black women" (Baugh 2015:761).
    
    % Non-racialized people drawing divisions between themselves and racialized people
      % Doing so while not focusing on oneself but rather on the group to which one belongs
        % Despite Lumbee Indians seeing themselves as not White, one Lumbee Indian, Lou, also distanced himself from Blacks, saying that "you got Indians on one side who just want to be Indians, they don’t want to fool with nobody else" and "they [Indians] didn’t fool with them [Blacks], they were scared of them" and "they [Indians] like to fight with Blacks" (Schilling-Estes 2004:178-179).

    % Racialized people being uneasy with labeling their identities
      % Becker's (2014) participant did not want to use the word African-American because it was reductive (i.e., African is a large continent with many cultures) (47)

    % Racialized people having poor speaking skills
      % A 20yo White woman working in a retail store spoke about how "[s]ome of the African Americans don't speak as well" and so are not really fit to work in a sales position (Williams & Connell 2010:367).

    % Essentializing language patterns to a racialized group
      % As the daughter of Trinidadian and Venezuelan parents, Blake (2016) found that she was not considered African-American enough to be accepted as an authentic speaker of AAE (153).

    \begin{itemize}
      \item[RQ3:] Is the discourse of Creoles and Cajuns in Louisiana indicative of Creoles being racialized?
    \end{itemize}

  \section{Analysis}
    \label{sec:discourse_analysis}
    The discourse of participants in this study suggests in many ways that Creoles have been racialized.
    In speaking of language, Creole-marked pronouns are consciously associated with Creoles and Cajun-marked pronouns with Cajuns.
    Stigma is also attached to those Creole speech patterns in very explicit ways.
    When defining what makes one a Cajun, race becomes fairly invisible.
    Factors generally include Acadian ancestry and cultural practices but not passing as White despite the latter being the strictest condition.
    In contrast, Creole is regularly equated to being Black despite this category being historically more open, a fact that many participants were aware of to at least some degree.
    Finally, while Creoles' and Cajuns' life experiences showed some similarities, the former often found themselves in lower status positions and were much more likely to be able to relate personal experiences of discrimination.

    %%% Language %%%

    % Recognition of differences between Creole and Cajun speech ------------------------------

    When speaking about language, both Creoles and Cajuns were able to speak of differences between each other.
    At times, these differences are downplayed, as in the statement in Sentence \ref{sent:different_speech_floyd} where Floyd Kerry, a Black Creole, focuses on local varieties being relatively similar unlike how they are both much different from how the French in Europe speak.
    Given the racialization of his identity, however, he has an incentive to promote closeness between the two groups rather than distance.
    This theme of acceptance of others came up more with Creoles than with others.

    \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
      \item FK: C'est pas un gros différence. To vois, ici dans la Louisiane, les Créoles et puis les Cadiens restent ensemble, ça fait les Cadiens et puis les Créoles, yé parlent pas la français comme les Français parlent le france. (52:36) \label{sent:different_speech_floyd}
      \item[] \longtrans{FK: It's not a big difference. You see, here in Louisiana, Creoles and Cajuns live together, so Cajuns and Creoles, they don't speak French like the French speak French.}
    \end{enumerate}
      
    % Arthur Rousseau
      % (52:43) [some Cajuns mix French and Creole]
      % INT: J'ai rencontré un homme, un Cadien. À mon oreille, il parlait créole en fait, mais il me disait, "Je parle français."
      % AR: Ouais, c'est un mélange de français et créole.
      % (53:21) [Creole is a dialect of French]
      % AR: C'est un dialecte.
    
    More often, though, participants were regularly able to distinguish.
    Oliver Lesage, a Cajun, offered two examples of Creole-marked speech in Sentences \ref{sent:different_speech_lesage1} and \ref{sent:different_speech_lesage2}.
    In the latter example, the switch involves him going from using \lexi{elle} to using \lexi{li} to refer to Mildred, showing the salience of subject pronouns in the distinction between the varieties.
    Also notable is that both of his demonstrations include the word \lexi{nègre}, whose translation in Louisiana is quite difficult.
    It has long been used in a rather term of endearment among Cajuns, even appearing in the refrain of the popular Cajun music song \song{Lâche pas la patate} released by Jimmy C Newman in 1973.
    It has also been used as a pejorative term.
    In this case, the intent was clearly endearment, but that it was thought be appropriate for articulating Creole speech either exemplifies a latent association, reinforces an association, or both.
    The term will be seen in a number of other examples, some that are more ambiguous and some that are less so.

    \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
      \item OL: Si t'olé parler en nègre, en créole, couru-vini, mo mo capable faire ça, aussi. (1:07) \label{sent:different_speech_lesage1}
      \item[] \longtrans{OL: If you want to speak in negro, in Creole, Couru-Vini, I'm capable of doing that, too.}
      \item OL: Elle s'appelle Mildred, alors quand elle elle arrive, là no gain pour parler comme ça. Li dit, ``Oliver, comment to yé, nègre?'' Et, ``M'apè fais okay aujourd'hui.'' (2:21) \label{sent:different_speech_lesage2}
      \item[] \longtrans{OL: Her name is Mildred, so when she arrives, then we have to talk like this. She says, ``Oliver, how are you, negro?'' And, ``I'm doing okay today.''}
    \end{enumerate}
