  % Possibly useful thematic references
    % Social meaning
      % Myers-Scotton (1988/2000) noted that the maintenance of various languages, dialects, and styles in a community likely comes down to all languages, dialects, and styles indexing social meanings that are useful to their speakers (127)
        % Similarly, L. Milroy (1980/1987) suggested that vernacular variants may still have social significance even when usage decreases in adulthood, as she suggests that women's usage of (th) in Belfast is still affected by their social network structure, even though their usage relative to men is much lower (206)
      % A social action is "a behavior to which people give meaning," taking into account the actions and reactions of individuals (Weber, as cited in Andersen & Taylor 2013:15)
        % The use of language can perhaps be seen as a social action that triggers social meanings
      % Definitions
        % Blom & Gumperz (1972/2000) defined social meaning as the social value implied when an utterance is used in a certain context (110)
        % Meaning in general has been defined as "the conventional association of distinctions in the world with distinctions in linguistic form" (Eckert & Labov 2017:469)
        % Social meaning has been defined as "the meaning of variation" (i.e., the meaning that is evoked through varying linguistic forms being used) (Eckert & Labov 2017:469)
        % For Eckert & Labov (2017), meaning and social meaning are both socially constructed, but the latter is different in that it's purely social (469)
      % Podesva (2011) suggested that a linguistic feature must be salient in order to acquire social meaning (235)
        % For phonetic features, he measured this through the extremeness of the value of the feature and the frequency of the feature (i.e., low frequency makes it noticeable when used) (Podesva 2011:237)
      % Eckert & Labov (2017) expand Agha's (2003) enregisterment concept to refer to how any linguistic form or element comes to have a social meaning
      % Macro-social variables have been argued to only have an indirect connection with social meaning in that the variation might index local qualities (e.g. refinement, toughness, etc.) that are linked to macro-social variables (e.g. toughness > men perhaps) (Eckert & Labov 2017:469-470)
      % A decontextualized sound has no social meaning but a sound in a given context can have social meaning (Eckert & Labov 2017:481)
      % In Terrebonne-Lafourche, Rottet (1995) expected French to end up having nothing more than "a purely symbolic function" (308)
      % Eckert (2000) believed that variants of linguistic variables can index social identity ("what people are") and/or participation in particular practices ("what people do") (139)
        % This turned into her indexical field, which is a way of visualizing the different types of meaning that a variable's realizations can have through diagrams (Eckert 2008 "Variation", as cited in Bell 2014:272)
      % Bell (2014) proposed a model of how social meaning is created through language that meshes with Labov's (1972) indicators, markers, and stereotypes, Agha's (2003) enregisterment, and Silverstein's (2003) orders of indexicality (269-270)
    % Identity construction
      % All the way back to Labov (1966/2006), he was already noting that two influences on language variation are the pressure to identify with a particular group and the need to conform to the overall hierarchy of values imposed by the community (291)
      % Frameworks
        % Mead viewed identity as being developed consistently throughout one's life via learning to play roles, one's self being divided into "I" (creative unique self) and "me" (passive conforming self) (as cited in Andersen & Taylor 2013:81-84)
        % Mendoza-Denton (2001) defines social identity as "the active negotiation of an individual's relationship with larger social constructs ... signaled through language and other semiotic means" (as cited in Androutsopoulos 2008 "Style":282)
        % Bricolage is the act of forming one's identity by improvising with the cultural resources that are available (Lévi-Strauss 1966, as cited i Bucholtz 2010:11)
          % Bricolage has been argued to be useful for constructing identities when the materials used already have associations with personae that make them meaningful (Zhang 2005:457)
        % Stance is "a social actor's public display of her or his orientation to ongoing interaction with respect to both the talk at hand and to the other participants" (Du Bois 2007, as cited in Bucholtz 2010:8)
          % Bucholtz (2010) argued that "stances serve as the building blocks of identity," in the sense that the combination of indexical stances leads to the construction of identity (8-9)
        % Performativity has been defined as constructing an identity "through a 'stylized repetition of acts'" (Butler 1988, as cited in C. Cutler 2007:527)
          % Bauman (2004) describes "performance" as "a display of communicative virtuosity" (as cited in Androutsopoulos 2008 "Style":285)
        % It has been suggested that how people relate themselves in contrast to out-group members was more important in defining an ethnicity than any internal attribute of the group (Barth 1969, as cited in Irvine & Gal 2000:74-75)
        % Bucholtz (1999) proposed two linguistic mechanisms for identity construction: negative identity practices and positive identity practices (211)
        % The acts of identity model is based on the idea that linguistic behavior reveals ones attempts to show solidarity with or difference from a group (Le Page & Tabouret-Keller 1985:14/182, slightly modified from Le Page 1968)
      % Examples
        % A high Afro-centrality index for African-American youths in Chapel Hill, NC did not lead to a statistically significant difference in their rate of use of AAE features, and in fact the coefficient suggested a decrease in rate as the index increased anyway (Van Hofwegen & Wolfram 2010:447)
        % In the South Carolina Sea Islands, a pair of speakers, one White and one Black, both were documented using (English-based) creole phonological features but only the Black speaker used creole morphosyntactic features (Rickford 1985, as cited in Fought 2013:390-391)
          % Fought concludes from this that these phonological features simply index island identity whereas the morphosyntactic features index Creole identity
        % German hip-hop forums, due to their "liminal" nature, provide spaces for users to "experiment with social identities and language styles in ways that are clearly outside their normal, everyday repertoire" (Androutsopoulos 2008 "Style":290)
        % 65% of the Peurto Ricans in NYC that Poplack (1979/1980/2000) interviewed felt positive about that identity, and while 90% felt that Spanish was very important, 60% still felt that being English monolingual was not a problem (218-219)
      % Examples not implicating race or ethnicity
        % Heath uses falsetto to create a flamboyant diva persona (Podesva 2007:489-490)
        % Blom & Gumperz (1972/2000) argued that Norwegians in Hemnesberget maintained two separate dialects because it allowed them to express cultural identities (109-110), specifically repeating that the local Ranamål dialect was linked to a local identity (as opposed to non-local)
          % This highlights the importance of location over ethnicity or race, something that may be in play in my data
    % Language prestige
      % Prestige has been defined as a value placed on a language variety in terms of it's usefulness specifically for social advancement (Weinreich 1953/1967:78-79)
      % Bourdieu (1977/1982) suggested that language varieties only obtain value via their distinctions from other varieties (41)
      % In Hemnesberget, Norway, Blom & Gumperz (1972/2000) found that the local variety of Norwegian, Ranamål, was more prestigious than other varieties for the residents (103) where residents would even make jokes about the way others spoke (111)
        % Ranamål is prestigious to locals despite it not being one of the two standard dialects of Norwegian that are legally sanctioned (Blom & Gumperz 1972/2000:103-104)
    % Insecurity
      % The reflexive stigma principle is the idea that the groups that use a stigmatized form the most tend to also stigmatize it the most (Labov 1966/2006:279/292)
      % Labov (1966/2006) found women in New York City to have more linguistic insecurity than men (320-322)
        % He measured this by providing a list of words and asking which pronunciation of these words is correct and which pronunciation they themselves use, the disagreements added up to form the insecurity index (95)
        % However, I would argue that he was identifying linguistic insecurity when he showed hypercorrection from the 2nd highest socioeconomic class (151-152)
          % Indeed, Labov (1966/2006) went on to say that his measure of linguistic insecurity had the 2nd highest socioeconomic group as the most insecure (320)
        % Eckert (2000) argued that the three social classes that tend to show linguistic insecurity are women, the lower middle class, and adolescents (29-30)
      % In terms of how one perceives their own speech, Labov (1966/2006) in 2006 argued based on self-reports not matching production that one often hears oneself say what one believes one should say, as opposed to using tangible feedback (313-315)
        % One example was Jewish participants in NYC who significantly over-stated their usage of prestige forms of vowels (Labov 1966/2006:312-313)
      % In Cusco, Peru, locals deny having features that are associated with rural Quechua-accented Andeans, which Delforge (2012) considers a case of erasure à la Irvine & Gal (2000) (315-316)
      % Neumann (1985) claimed that White creolophones were more ashamed of their speech than Black creolophones and so were less likely to pass it on to their children (42)
