      % Eckert & McConnell-Ginet (1992) argued that gender differences in language arise out of both dominance and (cultural) difference in that these two concepts feed into each other (462)
        % This could be generalized to any social situation where there are differences
        % Eckert & McConnell-Ginet (1992) argued that dual-culture theory, in their case the difference approach to women's language, deals with power differentials in that it could predict that oppressed people are more aware of the norms of their oppressors than vice versa, but it doesn't give enough agency to actors in order for there to be any blame (467)
