      % In San Antonio, Ecuador, one informant associated Quichua with Indianness, rural poverty, and femininity but Spanish with urban progress and masculinity (Rindstedt & Aronsson 2002:737)
      % Le Page & Tabouret-Keller (1985) proposed the following steps for a language variety becoming linked to an ethnicity: A group is named according to provenance, ancestry, phenotype, or traditions, then their linguistic behavior is described adjectively with said name, then the name becomes a noun and gains social connotations, then the language is separated from the group but maintains the connotations, and finally the language can become reified (235-236)
